snippet.textDisplay:
I was born on a Dublin street where the royal drums did beat,
And those loving English feet they tramped all over us,
And each and every night when me father came home tight
He'd invite the neighbors outside with this chorus:
Come out ye Black and Tans, come out and fight me like a man,
Show your wife how you won medals down in Flanders,
Tell them how the IRA made you run like hell away
From the green and lovely lanes of Killashandra.
Come tell us how you slew them poor Arabs two by two,
Like the Zulus they had spears and bows and arrows,
How you bravely faced each one with your 16-pounder gun,
And you frightened them poor natives to their marrow.
Come out ye Black and Tans, come out and fight me like a man,
Show your wife how you won medals down in Flanders,
Tell them how the IRA made you run like hell away
From the green and lovely lanes of Killashandra.
Come let us hear you tell how you slandered great Parnell,
When you thought him well and truly persecuted,
Where are the sneers and jeers that you bravely let us hear
When our heroes of '16 were executed?
Come out ye Black and Tans, come out and fight me like a man,
Show your wife how you won medals down in Flanders,
Tell them how the IRA made you run like hell away
From the green and lovely lanes of Killashandra.
Well the day is coming fast and the time is here at last,
When each yeoman will be cut aside before us,
And if there be a need, sure me kids would sing, "Godspeed, "
With a verse or two of Stephen Behan's chorus:
Come out ye Black and Tans, come out and fight me like a man,
Show your wife how you won medals down in Flanders,
Tell them how the IRA made you run like hell away
From the green and lovely lanes of Killashandra.

snippet.textDisplay:
I’m Jewish and don’t celebrate Christmas, but I think the holiday time is a joyous for all of us, no matter what you celebrate.

This year, the most poignant moment of the season for me was when a homeless man came on the subway during my commute to work on the morning after Christmas. He quietly wished everyone a happy holiday and sang a short hymn for the car. As he walked around with his hat out, I gave him some spare change, as did the woman next to me. After he left, she turned to me and commented that she usually never gave money to these people but something about him was endearing, and she felt a pull to donate to him. Privately, I echoed the sentiment.

Even with all the glitz and glamour of the holidays, receiving tips at work, seeing twinkling lights everywhere and having Mariah Carey playing in every department store... that small moment was what made it really feel like “Christmas” again, and i know the woman who sat next to me felt it too.

It truly isn’t about what you get, it’s what you give.

Wishing you all a very happy and meaningful holiday season, God bless.

snippet.textDisplay: There is one thing I would like Her Majesty to be mindful of next year, when she delivers her Christmas Message. I remember her, in 2015, saying VJ Day. May 8 is noted as VE Day, and the 75th Anniversary of that comes next year, but August 15th should be called VP Day not VJ Day. I feel uncomfortable, as she talks of VJ Day for this reason, the British Royal Family has a long relationship with the Japanese Royal Family, in fact, when the Showa Emperor (as Crown Prince) visited England in 1921, Her Majesty's Uncle sat on the bed and had an intimate conversation with him. The Heisei Emperor (now Emperor Emeritus) attended Her Majesty's Coronation, in 1953, and I remember seeing a picture of the Showa Emperor riding in a carriage with Her Majesty during his state visit to Britain in 1972. I also recall reading The Silver Drum, written by the Showa Emperor's Sister-in-Law, who said that Her Majesty asked "How's Ichiroo?" (The Showa Emperor's youngest brother) and I found it disturbing that somebody who could ask with genuine interest how the Showa Emperor's youngest brother was could be as undiplomatic as to say, "VJ Day" in a Christmas Message.
